<l>teṉparatavar miṭalcāya</l>
<l>vaṭavaṭukar vāḷōṭṭiya</l>
<l>toṭaiyamai kaṇṇit tiruntuvēṟ ṟaṭakkaik</l>
<l>kaṭumā kaṭaiiya viṭupari vaṭimpi</l>
<l>ṉaṟṟārk kaḷḷiṉ cōḻaṉ kōyiṟ</l>
<l>putuppiṟai yaṉṉa cutaicey māṭattup</l>
<l>paṉikkayat taṉṉa nīṇakar niṉṟe</l>
<l>ṉarikkūṭu mākkiṇai yiriya voṟṟi</l>
<l>yeñcā marapiṉ vañci pāṭa</l>
<l>vemakkeṉa vakutta valla mikappala</l>
<l>mēmpaṭu ciṟappi ṉaruṅkala veṟukkai</l>
<l>tāṅkātu poḻitan tōṉē yatukaṇ</l>
<l>ṭilampā ṭuḻantaveṉ ṉirumpē rokkal</l>
<l>viraṟceṟi marapiṉa cevittoṭak kunaruñ</l>
<l>cevittoṭar marapiṉa viraṟceṟik kunaru</l>
<l>maraikkamai marapiṉa miṭaṟṟiyāk kunaru</l>
<l>miṭaṟṟamai marapiṉa varaikkiyāk kunaruṅ</l>
<l>kaṭuntē rirāma ṉuṭaṉpuṇar cītaiyai</l>
<l>valittakai yarakkaṉ vauviya ñāṉṟai</l>
<l>nilañcēr mataraṇi kaṇṭa kuraṅkiṉ</l>
<l>cemmukap peruṅkiḷai yiḻaippolin tāaṅ</l>
<l>kaṟāa varunakai yiṉitupeṟ ṟikumē</l>
<l>yiruṅkiḷait talaimai yeyti</l>
<l>yarumpaṭa revva muḻantataṉ ṟalaiyē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>  When, (9d) </l>
<l>in the palace of the Cōḻa with good garlands [and] toddy, (5)</l>
<l>[his realm] within borders [reachable] by the motion set free when a fast horse is driven, (4)</l>
<l>with broad hands, a perfect spear [and] a chaplet suitable for [its] linking, (3)</l>
<l>who drove away by [his] sword the northern Vaṭukar (2)</l>
<l>while the strength of the southern fishermen was exhausted, (1)</l>
<l>in the storied building made with plaster [as white] as the new crescent moon, (6)</l>
<l>I stood in the tall mansion that was like a dewy pond, (7)</l>
<l>elusively(?) pressed my Kiṇai drum that unites with softness(?) (8)</l>
<l>[and] sang the Vañci according to undeficient custom, (9)</l>
<l>he was one to pour without guarding (12a-c)</l>
<l>the wealth ofg precious vessels/ornaments of superb quality, (11)</l>
<l>very many that wwere not those he distributed, designating [them] as for us (10).</l>
<l>	Seeing that, (12d)</l>
<l>of my very big kinfolk that had born poverty (13)</l>
<l>there were those who began ???, (14)</l>
<l>those who tightened [there] fingers ???, (15)</l>
<l>those who bound [their] throats ???, (16)</l>
<l>and those who bound [their] middles ???, (17)</l>
<l>May we obtain a smile difficult to end (22)</l>
<l>that flourishes like the jewels for the red-faced big clans (21)</l>
<l>of the monkeys who saw a woman’s ornament lying on the ground (20)</l>
<l>at the time when the Rakṣasa befitting in strength has snatched (19)</l>
<l>Sītā, united with Rāma with fast chariot, (18)</l>
<l>on top of the suffering of trouble [and] difficult affliction, (24)</l>
<l>reaching leadership among the big kin. (23)</l>
</lg>
